<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  The credential-acquisition build
  (<a href="/backlog/483-webidentity-project-credential-management-protocol/">#483</a> /
  <a href="/backlog/496-webidentity-build-design-credential-acquisition-protocol-con/">#496</a>, both
  resolved) deliberately <strong>omits</strong> a Configurator domain — technical defaults ride the
  <code>CustomCredentialProvider</code> registry + config-flavors.
  <a href="/backlog/499-identity-ceremony-configurator-domain-plateau-app-explore-on/">#499</a> asks:
  <em>if a real authoring need emerges — authors tuning passkey / FedCM enrollment flows
  <strong>without writing a plug</strong> — what would an identity-ceremony domain in the plateau-app
  Technical Configurator expose, and is the data-driven domain pattern (seed + provider entry, like the
  <code>webvalidation</code> / file-upload domain
  <a href="/backlog/725-port-the-webvalidation-plug-domain-its-subsystems-into-fronti/">#725</a>) the
  right shape?</em>
</p>

<h2>Why this is a research subject (not a park, not low-priority)</h2>
<p>
  The #499 review classified this seam as <strong>research-gated</strong>: it is <em>not</em>
  <code>priority: low</code> (a guessed enrollment-config default would be wrong, not merely low-value) and
  <em>not</em> a <code>maturityGated</code> park (it is not waiting on adoption — it is waiting on a
  prior-art survey we can do <strong>now</strong>). The seam here is <strong>authoring</strong> — how a
  non-coder configures an enrollment ceremony — which is distinct from the credential-acquisition
  <em>protocol</em> and the <code>webidentity</code> <em>project</em>, each already its own research
  subject.
</p>

<h2>Prior art to survey</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Web platform (authoritative).</strong> WebAuthn / passkeys registration ceremony
    (<code>navigator.credentials.create</code> and the <code>PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions</code>
    surface: RP, user, <code>authenticatorSelection</code>, <code>attestation</code>,
    resident-key / discoverable-credential, <code>userVerification</code>) and <strong>FedCM</strong>
    (<code>navigator.credentials.get</code> with an IdP config endpoint). These define the author-facing
    <em>axes</em>. Survey which options are author-meaningful vs impl-detail, and which are policy
    (UV required vs preferred) vs branding (RP name / icon).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Low-code identity tooling (benchmark).</strong> The <em>shape</em> hosted identity platforms use
    to expose enrollment-flow configuration to non-coders — knob-form vs visual flow vs policy matrix —
    surveying the author-surface shape, not the vendor.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>In-repo (the candidate home).</strong> The plateau-app <strong>Technical Configurator</strong>
    data-driven domain (seed + provider entry), as shipped for <code>webvalidation</code> / file-upload
    (#725). Confirm whether an identity domain is a clean instance of that pattern or needs a new seam.
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>Survey results (executed 2026-06-23)</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    <strong>Which axes are author-facing?</strong> A <em>small, policy-shaped</em> set:
    <code>userVerification</code> (required / preferred / discouraged), <code>residentKey</code> /
    discoverable, <code>authenticatorAttachment</code> (platform vs cross-platform),
    <code>attestation</code> (enterprise tier only), FedCM <code>mediation</code> (optional / required /
    silent), and <code>timeout</code>. Everything else is <strong>branding</strong>
    (<code>rp.name</code> / icon — the wrong tool for a decision-aid) or <strong>impl-only</strong>
    (<code>challenge</code>, <code>user.id</code>, <code>pubKeyCredParams</code>,
    <code>excludeCredentials</code> — the provider's job). FedCM's real config lives in the IdP config
    file, which the RP author does not write; it contributes essentially one shared axis
    (<code>mediation</code>).
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Policy or flow surface?</strong> <strong>Policy.</strong> Every author-facing axis is a single
    enumerated choice on an independent knob — no ordering, no branching. This is a knob-matrix, not an
    ordered-step flow, mapping straight onto the Configurator's <code>Axis</code> model. (The flow-builder
    tooling that exists — e.g. Descope's visual editor — solves multi-step orchestration + branded screens,
    a different problem.)
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Clean instance or new seam?</strong> <strong>Clean instance, zero new mechanism.</strong> The
    author-facing axes map directly onto <code>Axis</code> objects (each a policy enum) and the credential
    families become the strategies declaring where each sits — adding the domain is exactly one seed module
    + one provider entry, no new seam.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Is there an authoring consumer yet?</strong> <strong>No.</strong> The constellation sweep is
    unambiguous: WE's only identity surface (the conformance demo) hardcodes its own provider; the plateau
    Technical Configurator's ~17 domains include none for identity; and the one credential-shaped plateau
    module is git-forge write-auth, a different problem. The #499 demand gate is unmet.
  </li>
</ol>

<h2>Recommendation (to ratify in #499)</h2>
<p>
  <strong>Hold on a concrete-consumer trigger</strong> — do <em>not</em> build now (a Configurator domain
  no author can reach, duplicating axes the <code>CustomCredentialProvider</code> registry + config-flavors
  already carry), and do <em>not</em> permanently dissolve (the survey proves the domain is now cheaply
  buildable — one seed + one provider entry — the moment a consumer appears). <strong>Un-park trigger:</strong>
  the first flagship / exercise-app flow that needs an author to tune passkey / FedCM enrollment policy
  <strong>without writing a plug</strong>. On that trigger the build is a ~1-day data task seeding the six
  author-facing axes. Confidence: <strong>high</strong> on both the shape and the absence of a consumer
  today.
</p>
